[2] WHO clinical case definition for suspected cases of EVD faulted
Date: Published Online 24 Jul 2015, accessed 17 Dec 2015
Source: The Lancet [edited]
http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(15)00160-7

The WHO clinical case definition for suspected cases of Ebola virus disease arriving at Ebola holding units: reason to worry?
Rony Zachariah, Anthony D Harries, Medecins sans Frontieres [MSF] Operational research unit, Brussels Operational Center, Luxembourg City, Luxembourg (RZ); International Union Against TB and Lung Disease, Center for Operational Research, Paris, France (ADH); and
London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, London, UK (ADH) <rony.zachariah@brussels.msf.org>

[Excerpts]
[T]he specificity of the WHO case definition was strikingly low at 31.5 percent (95 percent CI 26â€¢0-37.6). This implies that 68 percent of patients who would be selected for admission to a holding unit would not actually have Ebola virus disease (false-positive results) -- indeed, a toss of a coin might have yielded a better chance of an accurate result. The clinical features of severe malaria, typhoid fever, and gastroenteritis can all mimic Ebola virus disease, all are probably prevalent in endemic areas, and many of those admitted to Ebola holding units are likely to have 1 of these illnesses. What is worrisome is that such patients who did not have Ebola virus disease would have been placed at high risk of exposure to Ebola virus within the holding unit, with this risk being commensurate with time spent in the unit waiting for the laboratory result. In Lado and colleagues' study, the median time for a laboratory result (in this case a semiquantitative Ebola virus reverse-transcriptase PCR) was 2 days (IQR 1-3), and interestingly 126 (15 percent) of the 850 admitted patients had no recorded result...
Operationally, if individuals are to be sent to hospital wards after being screened for Ebola virus disease, there must be absolute confidence that they do not have the disease (which needs maximum diagnostic sensitivity). Conversely, if people are being screened for admission to Ebola holding units with mediocre levels of infection control, there must be absolute confidence that they do have Ebola virus disease (necessitating maximum diagnostic specificity). The availability of such a test will be crucial in future Ebola outbreaks.
--
