*******
[4] Epidemiology, prevention, vaccination

Epidemiology
--------
17 Dec 2015 Liberia: Female survivor may be cause of Ebola flare-up in Liberia
http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-liberia-idUKKBN0U02EJ20151217?rpc=401
[According to experts investigating the case, an outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in Liberia months after the country was declared free of the virus could have stemmed from a survivor ("OG"), the mother of "NG," the index case of the latest Liberian outbreak (November 2015). "OG" (who is still alive) may have become infectious again after her immune system was weakened by pregnancy. A main hypothesis for the new cases is OG's "recrudescence", meaning a surge in virus replication from a dormant state, thought to be linked to a weakened immune system.

According to this theory, "OG" caught Ebola more than a year ago from her brother who died of a presumed Ebola infection in July 2014. She is then believed to have recovered, but the virus flared up again this year while she was pregnant. Antibodies fighting the virus tend to drop towards delivery.

It is not known exactly how she might have transmitted the virus, which is found in body fluids, to her family. According to experts, the theory means there can be no let-up in the monitoring of survivors for months or even years to come. According to Jonathan Heeney, Professor of Comparative Pathology at Cambridge, who has written about human reservoirs of the virus, "The affected countries want to say they are Ebola-free but they need help with continuing surveillance and health care monitoring. If you turn your back on this, you will see more of these cases."

The sources say another possible explanation is a secret sexual relationship between a family member and another survivor, although interviews have so far yielded few clues.]

*******
18 Dec 2015 Liberia: UNHCR and Liberia resume repatriation of Ivorians after Ebola hiatus
http://allafrica.com/stories/201512181422.html
[On 18 Dec 2015, the UNHCR (United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees) and Liberia resumed the voluntary repatriation of 10s of 1000s of Ivorian refugees, held in camps, from Liberia. The returns had been interrupted for more than 1 year by the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak. Approximately 11 000 of the 38 000 Ivorian refugees in Liberian camps have said they wish to return immediately. Convoys have begun taking refugees to Cote d'Ivoire. Did not a single one of them get EVD? - Mod.JW]

Prevention
-----
18 Dec 2015 Canada: ends Ebola screening for travellers from Liberia, Sierra Leone
https://ipolitics.ca/2015/12/18/canada-ends-ebola-screening-for-travellers-from-liberia-sierra-leone
[Canada is dropping an Ebola screening requirement for travellers coming from Liberia and Sierra Leone, but is keeping it in place for Guinea]

Vaccination
-----
18 Dec 2015: Ebola vaccination
http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2815%2901243-X/abstract

Citation. Fitzgerald F, Yeung S, Gibb D. (19 Dec 2015) Ebola vaccination. _The Lancet, Volume 386, No. 10012,_p2478. DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(15)01243-X

We welcome the results from the _Ebola ca Suffit_("Ebola that is enough") trial, emphasising the potential importance of a vaccine in controlling Ebola virus disease. However, parallel development in children and adolescents is scarce. More than 3000 confirmed cases of Ebola virus disease in children younger than 14 years have been reported, including cases documented in the trial, which might have been prevented if these children had been vaccinated.

Phase 1/2 safety data in children are urgently needed for candidate vaccines, and could be incorporated into ongoing trials. Only 1 paediatric trial is registered (NCT02509494). Although the first Ebola vaccines in human beings were appropriately done in adults, subsequent over-cautious paediatric development plans risk vaccine protection being denied to more than 40 percent of the population in affected regions. Experience with adenovirus and modified vaccinia Ankara virus vectors in children is extensive with a favourable safety profile. In view of the high fatality rates for Ebola virus disease in young children, the potential benefit of vaccination and scarcity of previous safety signals, active development is appropriate and necessary...

[Compiled by Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

